Medical help may in some instances be accompanied by [[embarrassment]].

==Features==
The source of this embarrassment or its range can vary from person to person. For some the embarrassment heightens when confronted by specific characteristics, such as a doctor of the opposite sex,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ghosh|first1=Partha|title=Transcultural Geriatrics: Caring for the Elderly of Indo-Asian Origin|date=2005|page=32}}</ref> while for others, the scope of their embarrassment may be exhaustive regardless of the social or peer group dynamics.<ref>{{cite book|last1=McVary|first1=Kevin|title=Contemporary Treatment of Erectile Dysfunction: A Clinical Guide|date=2010|page=69}}</ref> For others, the embarrassment factor may be overarching, especially when at a disadvantaged socioeconomic situation, for example one who needs financial assistance to obtain medical help.<ref>Medical Group Management Journal - Volumes 38-39 - Page 40, 1991</ref> In these scenarios the embarrassment may be duplicated due to a possible scenario wherein they are to be examined by both a doctor and perhaps if underage, a parent,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Robin|first1=Arthur|title=ADHD in Adolescents: Diagnosis and Treatment|date=1998|page=315}}</ref> or if an adult of [[poverty|low socioeconomic circumstances]], perhaps a social worker.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kent|first1=Bessie|title=Social Work Supervision in Practice|date=2014|page=25}}</ref>

