'''Ravi Arimilli''' (born 1963) is an [[IBM Fellow]] and Chief Architect. Largely responsible for development of the [[POWER5]], he is one of the most [[List of prolific inventors|prolific inventors]] in the world, being awarded 78 patents in 2002 and a further 53 in 2003. He has over 507 patents to his name and is listed among the most [[List of prolific inventors|prolific inventors]] in the world as measured by U.S. utility patents.<ref>[http://patft.uspto.gov/netacgi/nph-Parser?Sect1=PTO2&Sect2=HITOFF&u=%2Fnetahtml%2FPTO%2Fsearch-adv.htm&r=0&p=1&f=S&l=50&d=PTXT&Query=apt%2F1+and+in%2FArimilli-Ravi-K$ USPTO Utility Patent Search for Ravi Arimilli]</ref>
Arimilli moved with his family to the United States from [[Andhra Pradesh]], India, in 1969. He studied at [[Louisiana State University]], and joined IBM in 1985. His expertise includes [[symmetric multiprocessing]] (SMP) system structures, [[CPU cache|cache]]/memory hierarchies and [[system bus]] protocols.
