'''Yabaku''' is a fairly enigmatic tribe out of ten prominent Türkic tribes enumerated by [[Mahmud al-Kashgari|Mahmut Kashgari]] (11th century) in the list describing the location of the Türkic polities from the borders of the [[Byzantine Empire|Eastern Roman Empire]] to the borders of China in the following sequence: i. [[Pechenegs|Bechen]] ([[Pechenegs|Badjinak]], hence their Greek designation "''Patzinakae''"), ii. Kyfchak ([[Kipchak people|Kipchak]], actually [[Cumans]] then roaming in the Russian steppe and modern Ukraine), iii. [[Oghuz Turks|Oguz]] (linguistic kin to Turkey's and Azerbaijan's Turks, then still north of Aral, and between [[Aral Sea|Aral]] and the [[Caspian Sea]]), iv. [[Kimek|Yemek]] ([[Kimek]] then in the [[Astrakhan Oblast|Astrakhan]] vicinity), v. Bashgyrt ([[Bashkirs|Bashkort]], in modern [[Bashkortostan]]), vi. [[Basmyl]], vii. [[Kayı tribe|Kai]], viii. Yabaku, ix. [[Tatars]], x. [[Kyrgyz people|Kyrgyz]] (linguistic kin also to modern Kazakh, as well as the [[Kyrgyz people|Kyrgyz]]). Kashgari also noted that "the Kai, ''Yabaku'', Tatar, and Basmyl are bilingual, speaking in Türkic alongside their own languages, while Kyrgyzes, Kyfchaks, Oguzes..." have their own "Türkic" languages, and the languages of Yemeks and [[Bashkirs|Bashkirts]] are close to them.<ref>M.Zakiev, ''"Origin of Türks and Tatars"'', p.69, 192, Moscow, "Insan", 2002, {{ISBN|5-85840-317-4}} {{ru icon}}</ref>
